{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires finding the force law for a freely jointed chain under adiabatic conditions. This necessitates first finding the partition function and entropy/internal energy as functions of extension and temperature, and then applying the adiabatic constraint (dS=0) to find the relationship between temperature and extension to derive the force.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "helper_1",
      "instructions": "Derive the canonical partition function Z(T, x) for a freely jointed chain of n segments of length l at temperature T and end-to-end distance x. From this, derive the expressions for the Helmholtz free energy A(T, x), the internal energy U(T, x), and the entropy S(T, x) as explicit functions of n, l, T, and x."
    },
    {
      "label": "helper_2",
      "instructions": "Using the entropy S(T, x) derived previously, apply the adiabatic constraint dS = 0 to find the mathematical coupling between temperature T and extension x. Specifically, determine the functional form of T(x) such that the entropy remains constant during an adiabatic process."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent agent must substitute the adiabatic coupling T(x) into the expression for the force. The force F must be calculated using the thermodynamic identity for an adiabatic process, which is F = (dU/dx)_S or F = - (dS/dx)_T * (dT/dx)_S * T (or more directly via the relation F = (d/dx) [U(T(x), x)]). Ensure the distinction between isothermal force (dF/dx at constant T) and adiabatic force (dF/dx at constant S) is maintained to reach the final power-law expression."
}

